[Polyhedron]
A three-dimensional object.

[Surface Area]
The measure of the total area of the sides of a three-dimensional object.
Since the surface area is the sum of the area of each face of a 3D object, it
is measured in units-squared (not units-cubed).

[Prism]
A polyhedron with parallel congruent bases and lateral faces that are
parallelograms.

[Base]
The bottom of a 3D geometric shape. If the top and bottom of the figure are
parallel, they are both labeled bases.

[Lateral Face]
Any face of a polyhedron that is not a base.

[Base Edge]
A line where two bases intersect.

[Lateral Edge]
A line where two lateral faces intersect.

[Surface Area of a Prism]
The surface area of a prism is equal to L + 2B, where L is the total lateral
area and B is the area of either base (which must be congruent, following the
definition of a prism).

[Lateral Area]
The total area of the lateral sides of a prism, equal to the perimeter of
either base multiplied by the height of the prism.

[Altitude]
The perpendicular segment that joins the planes of the bases. The length of
the altitude is the height of the figure.

